<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1914-10-24T23:59:59-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1914-10-24T00:00:00-05:00" n="938" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d938">
                        <note rend="inline" type="source">File No. 812.00/13580.</note>
                        <head>
                            <hi rend="italic">The <gloss type="from">Acting Secretary of
                                    State</gloss> to Special Agent <persName type="to">Canova</persName>.</hi>
                        </head>
                        <opener>
                            <seg rendition="#center">[Telegram.]</seg>
                        </opener>
                        <opener>
                            <dateline rendition="#right">
                                <placeName>
                                    <hi rend="smallcaps">Department of State</hi>, <lb/>
                                    <hi rend="italic">Washington</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1914-10-24">
                                    <hi rend="italic">October 24, 1914</hi></date>.</dateline>
                        </opener>
                        <p>Your October 22, 7 p.m. Mr. Silliman’s telegram of October 7, 5 p.m., to
                            Mr. Fabela, is a restatement of the Department’s desires as expressed in
                            its telegram to the Brazilian Minister on September 22, 9 p.m., in which
                            is clearly set forth the wishes of this Government respecting the
                            evacuation. If the Convention has not a copy of the Department’s
                            September 22, 9 p.m. to the Brazilian Minister, Acting Foreign Minister
                            Fabela should be asked by the Convention to furnish such a copy.</p>
                        <p>Repeat this telegram to Carothers as reply to last paragraph of his
                            October 23, 9 a.m.</p>
                        <closer>
                            <signed>
                                <hi rend="smallcaps">Robert Lansing</hi></signed>.</closer>
                    </div>
